CREATED:20260225T081039Z
DESCRIPTION:The Program in Literature and the John Hope Franklin Humanitie
 s Institute present\n\nFredric Jameson and the Future of Critical Theory\
 n\nA three day conference featuring keynotes and panels\n\nApril 10 - 12\
 , 2026\nRichard White Auditorium\nDuke University\nEast Campus\n\nFriday\
 , April 10\n1:00pm - 6:30pm\n\nSaturday\, April 11 \n9:00am - 6:35pm\n\nS
 unday\, April 12\n9:00am - 3:45pm\n\nPlease register here\, or by using t
 he QR code on the flyer \nhttps://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSfQ9XO
 DYZZBoxrsijlo328EvGxlu5fKDBeJwLtFzl6ENPi2NQ/viewform \n\nThe conference s
 chedule is located here\nhttps://www.fredricjamesonandthefutureofcritical
 theory.org/schedule \n\nKeynotes by Michael Denning\, Jane Gaines\, Achil
 le Mbembe\, Toril Moi\, and Gayatri Chakravorty Spivak\n\nFredric Jameson
  (1934-2024) insisted on "imagining a future which might be radically and
  constitutionally other." The urgency of this task rested on his understa
 nding of Critical Theory "as a way of keeping the negative alive in a per
 iod in which praxis\, the unity of the negative and the positive\, itself
  seems suspended." Over the years\, Critical Theory has received scholarl
 y and popular attention\; it has simultaneously been pronounced dead and 
 an enduring threat. We invite scholars\, including students\, to join us 
 at Duke University for a three-day celebration of Fredric Jameson's endur
 ing legacy-and to keep imagining\, with him\, the future of Critical Theo
 ry.\n\nThe conference is organized by Duke's Graduate Program in Literatu
 re\, where Jameson taught for forty years\, and the John Hope Franklin Hu
 manities Institute. We acknowledge the generous support of the Holberg Pr
 ize Committee\, Norway.\n\nRegistration is now open.\n\nWe invite scholar
 s\, students\, and members of the public to join us in Durham for three d
 ays of conversation\, reflection\, and debate.
DURATION:PT9H30M
